{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512972","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512972"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:03:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:03:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11983"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11983","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11983"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.07,0,0.15,0.75]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4573"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115155"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4573","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4573"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11983"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97163"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"191"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6857"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7141"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15339"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48686"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115155","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115155"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman comes to see her regular general practitioner with ongoing concerns about her weight. She has been attempting to lose weight for the past 18 months, after deciding she wanted to improve her overall health for the sake of her three young children. She has made efforts to improve her lifestyle, including dietary modification (with the input of a dietician), going for daily 30 minute walks and cutting out alcohol. Over the past 18 months, she has lost 4kg, but is not satisfied with this result, appearing quite dejected by the progress.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer medical history includes hypertension (148/94 mmHg today) and obesity (current BMI of 42). The patient has had several conversations with her doctor over the past 18 months about her weight and would like to understand what would be the most effective strategy to achieve and maintain good long-term weight loss.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following management strategies would be most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tell the patient to continue what she is doing, no further intervention required","Refer to a dietician for further advice regarding dietary modification","Advise the patient to try the keto diet","Prescribe semaglutide","Refer to surgeon to assess suitability for bariatric surgery"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has concerns about her weight and has been actively trying to lose weight for 18 months with little effect. She is unhappy with her progress and is already potentially starting to experience adverse effects due to her weight, as evidenced by her hypertension. Therefore, advising the patient to \u003Cstrong\u003Econtinue current management\u003C/strong\u003E is not the correct option here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe stem states that the patient has already sought advice from a dietician about modification to her diet, so \u003Cstrong\u003Ereferring to a dietician\u003C/strong\u003E is also not correct here. Furthermore having already seen a dietician, it is likely they would have explored dietary options for the patient, so the GP advising the patient to try a \u003Cstrong\u003Eketo\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Ediet\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESemaglutide\u003C/strong\u003E is a GLP-1 agonist shown to be useful in inducing and sustaining weight loss in patients with obesity. While this is a valid treatment option here, this patient has a BMI of 42 and the most effective means of losing weight and maintaining the weight loss will be some form of metabolic bariatric surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer here is \u003Cstrong\u003Ereferral to a surgeon to assess suitability for weight loss surgery\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient meets the Medicare criteria and as such is eligible for bariatric surgery in the public system.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn the public health care system the following criteria must be satisfied for public bariatric surgery:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ehave either a body mass index (BMI) greater than 40, or more than 35 with two or more morbid obesity-related comorbidities;\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ebe aged between 18 and 65 years;\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ehave tried but failed to achieve or maintain clinically beneficial weight loss using non-surgical measures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bariatric surgery can be a good option for patients with obesity who have been unsuccessful in losing weight."],"references":["Swannell K. Lack of public bariatric surgery potentially \u201csubstandard care\u201d. Insight. 15.8.22. https://insightplus.mja.com.au/2022/31/lack-of-public-bariatric-surgery-represents-substandard-care/","Mehta, A., Marso, S. and Neeland, I., 2016. Liraglutide for weight management: a critical review of the evidence. Obesity Science \u0026 Practice, 3(1), pp.3-14.","Healthdirect.gov.au. 2022. Guide to bariatric surgery. [online] Available at: \u003Chttps://www.healthdirect.gov.au/guide-to-bariatric-surgery\u003E [Accessed 21 September 2022].","Grima M, Dixon JB. Obesity  Recommendations for management in general practice and beyond. Aust Fam Phys 2013; 42:532-41.","Elmaleh-Sachs A, Schw\u00e4tz JL, Bramante CT, et al Obesity Management in Adults A Review. JAMA. 2023; 330:2000-2015."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97163"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11983"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97163","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97163"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-22T19:40:59+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-22T19:41:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4573"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115155"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing infor